1
00:00:01,177 --> 00:00:03,700
Foundation Course 2, Talk 1.

2
00:00:04,740 --> 00:00:07,224
Moods, Emotions and Feelings.

3
00:00:09,967 --> 00:00:13,990
If there is one thing we are generally aware of, it is our prevailing state of mind.

4
00:00:14,851 --> 00:00:18,954
The mood and emotional states with the feelings they cause us to experience in the body.

5
00:00:20,135 --> 00:00:29,024
Moods, emotions and feelings tend to dominate our lives and we often gauge our quality of life by how much we are enjoying or not enjoying the way we are living.

6
00:00:30,085 --> 00:00:37,871
If a person has a continual problem with depression, lack of energy, listlessness, life seems useless, pointless, and hard to bear.

7
00:00:39,012 --> 00:00:48,500
If a person is fiery, ebullient, energetic, goal-orientated, life is a constant challenge, a fight, and it is somehow worthwhile, even when it's bruising.

8
00:00:50,101 --> 00:00:56,548
If a person is well-adjusted, not experiencing deep lows or great highs, problems don't seem to affect their emotional life so much.

9
00:00:57,469 --> 00:00:59,130
They can take things in their stride.

10
00:01:00,460 --> 00:01:04,918
We can go on delineating different personality types till the cows come home.

11
00:01:07,048 --> 00:01:10,722
It is a good exercise, by the way, to try and see what our own individual make-up is.

12
00:01:11,918 --> 00:01:16,463
But here we're interested to see if there's any inner pattern of mental states common to all humans.

13
00:01:17,165 --> 00:01:20,909
Is there a rationality, a viable syndrome of emotions and moods?

14
00:01:21,370 --> 00:01:26,055
If there is, perhaps it will be easy for us to see where we are in the scope of things.

15
00:01:26,075 --> 00:01:34,266
Perhaps it will make the job of purifying our minds a little easier if we can see our particular behaviour within the whole realm of human emotional experience.

16
00:01:34,847 --> 00:01:37,251
After all, this is the purpose of the middle path.

17
00:01:37,972 --> 00:01:45,320
This was the Buddha's avowed aim, to see what suffering is, what the cause, the way out of it, and the final experience of a state beyond suffering.

18
00:01:47,304 --> 00:01:55,492
We shall concentrate on a particular area of those moods and emotions and feelings, those that are associated with sensual pleasure and pain.

19
00:01:57,135 --> 00:02:00,197
Before we go on, we need to be clear in our minds what we're talking about.

20
00:02:01,218 --> 00:02:07,947
For the sake of clarity, let us call mood generalized states of mind that do not seem to be under our control.

21
00:02:08,483 --> 00:02:14,632
I may wake up depressed for no apparent reason, although all the outward signs of life are very comfortable, supportive and happy.

22
00:02:15,152 --> 00:02:18,617
A happy family, close relationships, good job and such like.

23
00:02:19,079 --> 00:02:21,682
Even so, my general mood is depression.

24
00:02:22,944 --> 00:02:24,747
Or it might be irritability.

25
00:02:25,487 --> 00:02:26,650
Or again, anxiety.

26
00:02:27,711 --> 00:02:33,539
No matter how much we try to calm ourselves, everything makes us feel more depressed, more irritated, more anxious.

27
00:02:34,361 --> 00:02:37,325
These moods just hang about sometimes all day, perhaps months.

28
00:02:38,251 --> 00:02:45,140
These are all part of the sankara group, the volitional conditionings that belong to the five skandhas, the aggregates.

29
00:02:47,003 --> 00:02:50,329
They are states of mind that are consequences of past actions.

30
00:02:51,730 --> 00:02:53,973
They are the karmic results of past behavior.

31
00:02:54,574 --> 00:02:57,158
That's why we can't do anything about them.

32
00:02:57,759 --> 00:03:02,646
That's why we have to sit patiently in the midst of these conditionings and just allow them to burn out.

33
00:03:03,628 --> 00:03:06,552
That's why we must be wary of our reactions to them.

34
00:03:06,701 --> 00:03:11,250
depressed about being angry, angry about being anxious, anxious about being depressed, and so on.

35
00:03:11,871 --> 00:03:18,342
These reactions are only fueling the process, either by indulging, entertaining these states, or by repressing them.

36
00:03:19,084 --> 00:03:21,268
And of course, it is of little help to take drugs.

37
00:03:21,949 --> 00:03:27,799
They just repress those states of mind, though there are times they can be used wisely to take the heat off.

38
00:03:29,314 --> 00:03:40,391
Now, emotions, also belonging to the Sankara Kanda, the aggregator of volitional conditionings, I'd like to define as less stable states of mind that surface and disappear fairly quickly.

39
00:03:41,234 --> 00:03:45,961
For instance, I might be fearful crossing the road, but the fear disappears once I'm on the other side.

40
00:03:47,122 --> 00:03:50,808
Someone may say something that triggers off an angry response, but I can just shrug it off.

41
00:03:51,849 --> 00:03:56,638
I put music on that creates an emotional state, but it passes quickly once the music stops.

42
00:03:57,832 --> 00:04:01,298
I'd like to include here those emotional responses we have to moods.

43
00:04:02,299 --> 00:04:07,506
So emotions may be less stable and we may be able to exercise some control over them.

44
00:04:09,627 --> 00:04:14,174
As for feelings, I'd like to define them as the effects of these moods and emotions on the body.

45
00:04:14,715 --> 00:04:15,816
It's the biofeedback.

46
00:04:16,798 --> 00:04:24,668
Heavy feelings associated with depression, hot feelings with anger, wobbly weak feelings of fear, tight feelings of anxiety and stress and so on.

47
00:04:25,492 --> 00:04:27,615
It's these feelings that drugs change.

48
00:04:28,497 --> 00:04:31,661
Drugs are only chemicals affecting the chemical composition of the body.

49
00:04:32,523 --> 00:04:37,050
They stop the expression of mental states in the body and so its feedback to the mind.

50
00:04:37,930 --> 00:04:39,473
In so doing, they repress it.

51
00:04:40,394 --> 00:04:44,600
That's why they don't help cure the state of mind, the actual moods and emotions themselves.

52
00:04:45,723 --> 00:04:52,072
But they do help in crises and in psychotic states of mind where they give back sufferers some control over their lives.

53
00:04:53,538 --> 00:05:00,446
For the meditator, these feelings are important, for they are the easiest things to center our attention on.

54
00:05:00,466 --> 00:05:08,213
By experiencing our states of mind, moods and emotions at the bodily feeling level, there is no indulgence, no repression going on.

55
00:05:09,196 --> 00:05:13,000
We are experiencing these states of mind at their raw issue.

56
00:05:13,781 --> 00:05:17,605
We are really experiencing these states of mind as they really are.

57
00:05:19,153 --> 00:05:26,262
If moods and emotions begin to affect our thinking, then our thinking becomes an expression of those moods and emotions.

58
00:05:26,983 --> 00:05:29,786
Unwittingly, the thinking develops those states of mind.

59
00:05:30,947 --> 00:05:34,351
We have to be careful not to let moods swamp our lives.

60
00:05:35,192 --> 00:05:38,956
To do that, we have to keep them at arm's length, so to speak.

61
00:05:38,976 --> 00:05:45,685
The easiest way to do this is to experience those moods and emotions as they manifest in the body as feelings.

62
00:05:47,267 --> 00:05:49,990
Concentrating on the feelings stops the mind thinking.

63
00:05:51,112 --> 00:05:58,521
This is what we are trying to do in meditation, in the meditative life, to develop a way of experiencing our moods and emotions in an objective way.

64
00:05:59,723 --> 00:06:10,896
So, if we accept these definitions of moods, emotions, with their attendant feelings for the purpose of this talk, we can now ask, where do these negative states of mind arise from in the first place?

65
00:06:13,153 --> 00:06:19,824
In the discourse on the turning of the wheel of the law, the Buddha makes it quite clear that the cause of all suffering is desire.

66
00:06:21,305 --> 00:06:23,930
This is the noble truth of the cause of suffering.

67
00:06:24,812 --> 00:06:32,944
The craving, which causes rebirth, accompanied by the pleasure of emotions, finds delight in this and that object.

68
00:06:34,165 --> 00:06:41,776
Want, desire, craving, obsession, all these attitudes, these internal dispositions, cause us suffering.

69
00:06:41,959 --> 00:06:48,127
Here we shall investigate how desire for sensual pleasure causes so many of our different moods and emotional states.

70
00:06:49,709 --> 00:06:51,069
Let's take a simple example.

71
00:06:52,872 --> 00:06:54,293
The little girl who wants ice cream.

72
00:06:54,834 --> 00:06:58,517
There she is in the front room playing quietly with one of those mind-boggling educational games.

73
00:06:59,399 --> 00:07:02,403
Suddenly the strum of the Italian gondola musico shatters the piece.

74
00:07:02,663 --> 00:07:03,803
She sits balls upright.

75
00:07:04,024 --> 00:07:05,206
She's caught and snared.

76
00:07:05,706 --> 00:07:11,713
Once the vision of the ice cream cornet has arisen in the imagination, little Lily is in a paroxysm of desire.

77
00:07:12,622 --> 00:07:18,307
This new pleasure, fuelled by experience of past similar pleasures of choc-ice and lollipops, obsesses her.

78
00:07:19,528 --> 00:07:20,370
I want an ice-cream.

79
00:07:21,430 --> 00:07:24,134
It is said with such force that Daddy is shocked and falls over.

80
00:07:25,456 --> 00:07:28,559
This I wanting the ice-cream is the ice-cream.

81
00:07:29,560 --> 00:07:32,442
The child, the I and the vision of the ice-cream are all one.

82
00:07:33,283 --> 00:07:35,406
The child at the younger age grasps this fact.

83
00:07:36,187 --> 00:07:37,228
Me ice-cream.

84
00:07:37,815 --> 00:07:40,139
In that phrase is the kernel of all our problems.

85
00:07:40,600 --> 00:07:44,507
It encapsulates all our wrong identification and our obsession.

86
00:07:45,127 --> 00:07:46,048
Our identity.

87
00:07:46,810 --> 00:07:47,110
Me.

88
00:07:47,411 --> 00:07:47,812
Ice cream.

89
00:07:50,154 --> 00:07:54,141
Let us take this path of indulgence.

90
00:07:54,161 --> 00:07:59,189
Daddy knows by past experience it's best to let her have her own way once in a while, or it's misery or mourning.

91
00:07:59,410 --> 00:07:59,911
He gives in.

92
00:07:59,971 --> 00:08:00,492
It's Sunday.

93
00:08:00,911 --> 00:08:01,874
He's too tired to fight.

94
00:08:02,514 --> 00:08:03,857
Lily's off and back in delight.

95
00:08:04,360 --> 00:08:08,144
Desire has arisen with all its attendant emotions of expectation and excitement.

96
00:08:09,045 --> 00:08:13,009
With the first lick there comes ecstatic delight, and with the final lick, total satisfaction.

97
00:08:13,730 --> 00:08:16,194
That is, until the desire for ice cream arises again.

98
00:08:17,514 --> 00:08:20,038
So here we have the first particular little merry-go-round.

99
00:08:20,639 --> 00:08:21,980
Desire and surfeit.

100
00:08:22,281 --> 00:08:24,543
A rest period, and desire arises again.

101
00:08:25,584 --> 00:08:28,887
If we investigate our lives, we shall see we spend a lot of time on this round.

102
00:08:29,629 --> 00:08:32,292
The regular cup of tea, desire and surfeit.

103
00:08:32,677 --> 00:08:34,200
The party once every so often.

104
00:08:34,721 --> 00:08:37,905
The TV programs, especially the soaps, live off this emotional round.

105
00:08:38,586 --> 00:08:39,808
A half hour is quite enough.

106
00:08:40,309 --> 00:08:45,458
Can you imagine attending a soap festival, Coronation Street, Dallas, for ten hours a day for seven days?

107
00:08:47,883 --> 00:08:51,909
The second merry-go-round is when one such pleasure begins to predominate.

108
00:08:52,772 --> 00:08:58,160
Sharpened by past satisfaction, this desire wants a keener pleasure or boredom will set in.

109
00:08:58,697 --> 00:09:02,864
We slowly become slaves to that desire, we become obsessed by it, we demand it.

110
00:09:03,585 --> 00:09:05,288
That is what the Buddha meant by attachment.

111
00:09:06,409 --> 00:09:11,437
We can actually feel the compulsiveness of craving of this attachment even if we miss a morning cup of tea.

112
00:09:12,339 --> 00:09:20,650
But when we look at how people become dedicated to beauty, wealth, fame or power, we can begin to see the whole such desires as craving can have.

113
00:09:21,994 --> 00:09:24,957
The reason is that desire has an inbuilt growth mechanism.

114
00:09:25,528 --> 00:09:31,736
Even Lily, the second time round, might want a different ice cream, or a bigger ice cream, and eat too much.

115
00:09:33,057 --> 00:09:35,902
We say in our consumerist society that we are spoiled for choice.

116
00:09:36,241 --> 00:09:41,828
The fact is, desire demands choice, for once a pleasure is had, its repeat is boring.

117
00:09:43,149 --> 00:09:51,340
The cycle, the round of pleasure surfeit, includes boredom, a demand for difference, and a difference that's better and more exciting.

118
00:09:52,282 --> 00:09:55,164
This comes home quite starkly when we look at popular films.

119
00:09:56,038 --> 00:09:58,621
The horror films of yesterday make us laugh now.

120
00:09:59,442 --> 00:10:01,225
Now we want real horror, real terror.

121
00:10:02,125 --> 00:10:06,711
But the next generation will be baffled at how such things were ever found to create fear.

122
00:10:07,412 --> 00:10:10,755
They'll laugh and demand even greater horror, a terror beyond terror.

123
00:10:13,139 --> 00:10:17,102
This second round can lead to overdosing, to overindulgence, and then to disgust.

124
00:10:17,984 --> 00:10:21,087
That one curry dish too many that turns a good meal into vomit.

125
00:10:22,028 --> 00:10:25,572
That one glass of whiskey that makes Sunday morning lying a bed of nails.

126
00:10:26,397 --> 00:10:30,522
It is interesting to note that in children desires are not so highly developed.

127
00:10:31,462 --> 00:10:33,544
They seem to be still in contact with their bodies.

128
00:10:34,586 --> 00:10:37,369
They seem to have a built-in body wisdom knowing when to stop.

129
00:10:38,289 --> 00:10:44,817
As we grow older we lose this distinction between bodily needs and mental greeds by way of continual overindulgence.

130
00:10:46,119 --> 00:10:54,327
Now this third round of desire to overindulgence, to disgust, is a particular interest in the role it can play in spiritual growth.

131
00:10:55,506 --> 00:11:03,580
It was exactly this disgust and weariness with courtly life that is said to have been the final goal that drove the Buddha to seek the end of suffering.

132
00:11:05,102 --> 00:11:09,951
He realized the insatiability of desire and the emptiness and despair of boredom.

133
00:11:11,413 --> 00:11:16,400
In our adult life, we often have such feelings about our jobs, our relationships and our very life.

134
00:11:16,802 --> 00:11:19,926
But it doesn't mean we have to leave our job, our spouse, or commit suicide.

135
00:11:20,807 --> 00:11:24,009
It means we have to look at our situation, our whole life situation.

136
00:11:24,551 --> 00:11:28,715
We have to discover why we suffer such feelings of boredom, of emptiness, of uselessness.

137
00:11:29,556 --> 00:11:36,163
Realising that it arising from this basic disposition to life, that of pleasure-seeking, is to liberate us from wrong view.

138
00:11:36,844 --> 00:11:37,403
It's a beginning.

139
00:11:38,245 --> 00:11:43,509
The struggle to free ourselves from its snares has only just begun, but this is the path of liberation.

140
00:11:44,171 --> 00:11:45,072
Liberation from what?

141
00:11:45,658 --> 00:11:48,543
From the belief that our desires can be satisfied.

142
00:11:49,645 --> 00:11:51,990
From desire, want, obsessions themselves.

143
00:11:52,711 --> 00:11:56,076
That lead eventually to dissatisfaction, suffering, dukkha.

144
00:11:58,501 --> 00:12:00,705
Now the next round is caused by denial.

145
00:12:01,888 --> 00:12:06,495
There's our little Lily, jumping up and down all happy and excited, shouting, I want an ice cream.

146
00:12:07,157 --> 00:12:07,998
Daddy's in a bad mood.

147
00:12:08,678 --> 00:12:09,000
No.

148
00:12:09,773 --> 00:12:10,875
What happens in Little Lily?

149
00:12:11,556 --> 00:12:12,878
At first there's a sense of shock.

150
00:12:13,678 --> 00:12:16,803
All those visions of steaming cool corn, it's burnt, melt down.

151
00:12:17,384 --> 00:12:18,265
All the excitement.

152
00:12:19,126 --> 00:12:20,970
The jumping is all suddenly squashed.

153
00:12:21,429 --> 00:12:22,172
The mind races.

154
00:12:22,412 --> 00:12:23,133
Options arise.

155
00:12:23,653 --> 00:12:25,537
She could try pleading bargaining ploy.

156
00:12:25,797 --> 00:12:27,038
Oh, please, Daddy, please.

157
00:12:27,559 --> 00:12:29,643
As if the world were heaving with terminal sorrow.

158
00:12:30,384 --> 00:12:30,604
No.

159
00:12:31,546 --> 00:12:33,148
I won't have a big one, just a small one.

160
00:12:33,248 --> 00:12:33,489
No.

161
00:12:34,529 --> 00:12:35,491
Next ploy, anger.

162
00:12:36,032 --> 00:12:36,452
Why not?

163
00:12:36,572 --> 00:12:37,114
I want one.

164
00:12:37,582 --> 00:12:40,087
Dad hasn't the stomach for a fight and tells her to go and ask Mum.

165
00:12:41,110 --> 00:12:42,293
On the way, Lily sweetens up.

166
00:12:43,134 --> 00:12:45,038
Mummy, can I have an ice cream, please?

167
00:12:45,559 --> 00:12:47,865
She knows Mummy's objections straight into bargaining.

168
00:12:48,186 --> 00:12:49,028
I'll eat all my dinner.

169
00:12:50,110 --> 00:12:51,172
Mummy knows she won't.

170
00:12:51,653 --> 00:12:51,813
No.

171
00:12:52,816 --> 00:12:54,118
Lily tries the angry stomp.

172
00:12:54,538 --> 00:12:55,562
I want an ice cream.

173
00:12:55,802 --> 00:12:58,106
Then the tantrum, screaming blue murder.

174
00:12:58,221 --> 00:13:01,086
Mummy knows this gambit and decides on the counter of ignoring it.

175
00:13:01,846 --> 00:13:10,458
Past experience has proven that giving in at this stage can lead to regular tantrum use, and to smack her leads to a noble fight to the death.

176
00:13:11,821 --> 00:13:12,642
Lily's very strong.

177
00:13:13,182 --> 00:13:13,903
Mummy ignores her.

178
00:13:14,423 --> 00:13:16,447
Lily finally exhausts herself and ends up weeping.

179
00:13:16,947 --> 00:13:19,731
The weeping begins to sound genuine, real sorrow.

180
00:13:20,432 --> 00:13:23,537
Mummy tries to console, but Lily won't hear of it.

181
00:13:24,039 --> 00:13:29,948
Slowly, the sorrow remoles itself into a quiet glowering, very glum, very quiet, very withdrawn.

182
00:13:30,850 --> 00:13:34,897
Full of resentment and self-pity, Lily sits incommunicado.

183
00:13:35,758 --> 00:13:37,760
The Great Depression is descending.

184
00:13:38,522 --> 00:13:41,405
She won't talk, and she certainly won't eat.

185
00:13:42,408 --> 00:13:46,774
She would have eaten if she'd had her ice cream, but now she hasn't, she can't eat.

186
00:13:47,195 --> 00:13:49,018
Can't, of course, means won't.

187
00:13:49,792 --> 00:13:53,697
At this point, Mummy relents a little, not wanting to crush Lily's spirit.

188
00:13:54,998 --> 00:13:58,261
A little explanation why such tactics won't get her the ice cream.

189
00:13:59,062 --> 00:14:01,625
And if she hadn't have lost her temper, she could have had one after dinner.

190
00:14:02,447 --> 00:14:03,307
And a little bargaining.

191
00:14:04,028 --> 00:14:05,951
She can still have one if she eats her food.

192
00:14:06,412 --> 00:14:07,613
Lots of pleas and cuddling.

193
00:14:07,952 --> 00:14:09,174
Little Lily relents.

194
00:14:09,615 --> 00:14:10,756
She accepts the situation.

195
00:14:11,277 --> 00:14:12,678
No ice cream now.

196
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:18,785
With this acceptance, you can sometimes catch the relief as the desire, the obsession leaves.

197
00:14:19,187 --> 00:14:20,070
This is letting go.

198
00:14:21,212 --> 00:14:29,250
But of course, the desire, the demand for ice cream lies dormant like a wild tiger, ready to spring upon the next time the ice cream van chimes.

199
00:14:32,076 --> 00:14:38,091
Now, as far as Lily is concerned, her desire for ice cream is proper and legitimate simply because the desire is there.

200
00:14:38,711 --> 00:14:41,135
Those who frustrate her desires are seen as enemies.

201
00:14:41,476 --> 00:14:43,580
They are seen as the direct cause for her suffering.

202
00:14:44,081 --> 00:14:46,244
The humiliation of begging and bargaining.

203
00:14:46,725 --> 00:14:49,009
The frustration and anger, the depression and sadness.

204
00:14:49,610 --> 00:14:51,854
All these are directly caused by mummy and daddy.

205
00:14:52,534 --> 00:14:55,219
This is the great lie we can't let go of.

206
00:14:55,198 --> 00:14:58,404
Even as adults, we still bear grudges against our parents.

207
00:14:58,846 --> 00:15:02,232
Even as adults, we believe the other is the cause of our unhappiness.

208
00:15:02,774 --> 00:15:05,238
But they are only the proximate causes, catalysts perhaps.

209
00:15:05,578 --> 00:15:10,288
The direct cause is ourselves, and the root cause is desire with its twin, aversion.

210
00:15:11,315 --> 00:15:15,000
Although we followed a typical little child, that little child is in all of us.

211
00:15:15,301 --> 00:15:16,022
This is the problem.

212
00:15:16,522 --> 00:15:17,984
We're still playing these gambits.

213
00:15:18,544 --> 00:15:22,049
We're still getting caught up in the meshes of desires, greeds and obsessions.

214
00:15:22,711 --> 00:15:24,813
We play these rounds out time after time.

215
00:15:25,335 --> 00:15:30,042
Some people never get tired of them, even consciously build their lives around them.

216
00:15:30,062 --> 00:15:35,369
Like the person who loves to fall in love, but as soon as it's serious, they're off.

217
00:15:35,389 --> 00:15:40,917
Even though leaving in the midst of infatuation is painful, the beginning of a new infatuation is too attractive.

218
00:15:41,302 --> 00:15:45,207
The crunch for such people comes with the loss of beauty, the inability to attract.

219
00:15:46,650 --> 00:15:56,365
We need to look at these little lilies inside us, see the child for what it is, remnants of past behaviour constantly cramping our lives with obsession for pleasure, for me, for mine.

220
00:15:57,587 --> 00:16:01,975
Somehow we have to change the child's behaviour, but not to crush its spirit.

221
00:16:03,658 --> 00:16:07,443
This re-education of the child in us is no easy matter.

222
00:16:08,486 --> 00:16:13,813
As children, we also learnt how to repress and bury our painful moods and feelings deep in our psyche.

223
00:16:14,715 --> 00:16:19,541
We learnt how to swallow our bad feelings, our hates, frustrations, fears, anxieties and so on.

224
00:16:19,561 --> 00:16:21,683
And they sit there, burning all the time.

225
00:16:23,065 --> 00:16:27,390
The Buddha taught that the human was made up of two parts, the physical body and the mind.

226
00:16:28,192 --> 00:16:29,994
He said the mix was like milk in water.

227
00:16:30,554 --> 00:16:33,399
They were inseparable, the mind infusing the body.

228
00:16:34,220 --> 00:16:36,182
When the mind moves, so does the body.

229
00:16:36,600 --> 00:16:38,504
When the body moves, so does the mind.

230
00:16:39,466 --> 00:16:43,494
If an angry thought arises in the mind, electrochemical changes are felt in the body.

231
00:16:44,054 --> 00:16:47,059
If pain arises in the body, the mind knows it and reacts.

232
00:16:48,081 --> 00:16:53,451
Everything in the body and mind interpenetrate when we see this, and it can be easily observed in meditation.

233
00:16:54,013 --> 00:16:56,937
Psychosomatic diseases are not hard to understand.

234
00:16:57,796 --> 00:17:10,153
When repressed, the distorted energy of negative moods and emotions have no expression, so they leak out of the mind, causing neurotic behavior, at worst, a psychotic breakdown, or they leak into the body, causing illness.

235
00:17:11,295 --> 00:17:20,749
Whenever suffering arises, be it physical or mental pain, our reactions of shock, of bargaining, of anger, of depression, will also arise.

236
00:17:20,897 --> 00:17:24,821
maybe in different order, in different strengths, maybe with one or two missed out.

237
00:17:25,583 --> 00:17:29,086
In extreme cases, our reactions may lead to despair and suicide.

238
00:17:29,866 --> 00:17:36,212
But in happier cases, like Little Lily, we will come to accept things as they really are and be peaceful with our situation.

239
00:17:38,394 --> 00:17:49,385
This is all part of what Buddhism calls samsara, the faring on, the going on and on, a continual moving from here to there, this restlessness that finds no peace.

240
00:17:49,905 --> 00:17:52,872
We need to see this vicious circle of pain-pleasure syndrome.

241
00:17:53,392 --> 00:17:56,377
This is samsara, the opposite of our goal, nibbana.

242
00:17:57,078 --> 00:18:00,885
One of the meanings of nibbana is nirvana, no desire.

243
00:18:02,930 --> 00:18:12,488
This particular round of shock-fear, bargaining-pleading, frustration-anger, depression, has been especially studied in people who are suffering from terminal illness.

244
00:18:13,362 --> 00:18:20,914
Every individual will have a particular reaction syndrome to loss, be it to dropping their ice cream, to the discovery that they have a terminal cancer.

245
00:18:22,057 --> 00:18:34,779
Although here we have concentrated on the sensual pleasure part of desire, don't forget that there is also the desire for life itself, the desire to become, and the desire to annihilate oneself, the death wish.

246
00:18:36,346 --> 00:18:40,771
The question now arises as to why some people suffer so much at death and dying.

247
00:18:41,614 --> 00:18:45,019
Others seek it and commit suicide, and yet others die peacefully.

248
00:18:45,799 --> 00:18:51,188
To understand this, we need to dig a little deeper and see exactly what happens when we desire something greatly.

249
00:18:52,368 --> 00:18:57,296
When Lily is caught up in the idea of wanting an ice cream, that's just the first expression of desire.

250
00:18:58,218 --> 00:19:04,547
But once she actually has the ice cream in hand, there arises an attachment to it, my ice cream.

251
00:19:05,319 --> 00:19:12,310
Asking Lily to share some of her ice cream with her brothers and sisters is to ask her to let go of a bit of that my, that me.

252
00:19:13,353 --> 00:19:24,390
By being generous, Lily is coming to understand that the ice cream doesn't actually belong to anyone, or rather that the concept of belonging, of possession, is fluid, not rigid.

253
00:19:25,632 --> 00:19:33,183
If when Lily's asked she won't share, and her brother and sister take by force, then we see how much Lily has invested herself in that ice cream.

254
00:19:34,075 --> 00:19:39,742
In other words, to take the ice cream off Lily is also to rob her of some of herself.

255
00:19:40,844 --> 00:19:45,130
It's to take a part of her away, hence the screaming, the fighting to the death.

256
00:19:46,411 --> 00:19:47,712
Do we change as we grow older?

257
00:19:48,334 --> 00:19:49,394
Unfortunately, not much.

258
00:19:50,096 --> 00:19:53,901
In fact, most of us, as we grow older, tend to become more childish.

259
00:19:54,741 --> 00:19:58,227
Listen to someone who's had their car scratched by hooligans or stolen.

260
00:20:00,468 --> 00:20:07,036
Underlying these reactions is this self-identity, and whenever that self-identity is threatened, fear arises.

261
00:20:07,537 --> 00:20:08,438
That's what fear is.

262
00:20:08,458 --> 00:20:13,663
It's this self-identity, this ego, the I, saying something is threatening it.

263
00:20:14,786 --> 00:20:18,049
If that threat is real and actually attacks, then there is trauma and shock.

264
00:20:18,891 --> 00:20:28,702
The difference is seen with the reaction to nearly being run over to actually being knocked down, to knowing the next door neighbours have been burgled, to being burgled oneself.

265
00:20:29,846 --> 00:20:32,451
This is what this self-identity, this ego, produces.

266
00:20:32,892 --> 00:20:36,457
Ego says, I am my house, my car, my jewellery.

267
00:20:36,978 --> 00:20:39,382
This is my wife, my husband, my child.

268
00:20:40,022 --> 00:20:44,730
The trauma, the shock is felt when such self-definitions are proved to be palpably untrue.

269
00:20:45,391 --> 00:20:49,897
When the car is stolen, when the spouse walks out, when the child grows up and leaves.

270
00:20:50,958 --> 00:20:54,903
Closer to home, this ego identifies with the body and mind.

271
00:20:55,304 --> 00:21:00,932
In fact, in the ultimate analysis, that's what ego is, what self, person, personality is.

272
00:21:01,614 --> 00:21:03,916
That's why dying is such a suffering for us.

273
00:21:04,719 --> 00:21:07,702
For this ego, this I, sees itself in mortal danger.

274
00:21:09,065 --> 00:21:13,191
This is what Queen Malika meant when she answered her husband, the king of Kosala.

275
00:21:14,011 --> 00:21:15,875
He had asked her whom did she love the most.

276
00:21:16,256 --> 00:21:17,116
She said herself.

277
00:21:17,823 --> 00:21:22,430
The king, far from being outraged, agreed that he too loved himself the most.

278
00:21:23,432 --> 00:21:25,075
Both approached the Buddha for advice.

279
00:21:25,915 --> 00:21:31,265
He said, unenlightened beings did indeed in the last analysis love themselves the most.

280
00:21:32,006 --> 00:21:33,208
Ego protects itself.

281
00:21:34,108 --> 00:21:38,195
Any movement of harm towards ego is signalled by fear and anxiety.

282
00:21:39,156 --> 00:21:42,041
Any actual wound causes trauma and shock.

283
00:21:42,680 --> 00:21:51,529
So we see that underlying all this sense pleasure, all this desire to become somebody, to be a personality, all rests on an elephant trap, death.

284
00:21:52,431 --> 00:21:55,413
That's why fear is the champion and guardian of ego.

285
00:21:56,115 --> 00:21:59,538
It will cause ego to fly for its life or fight to the death.

286
00:22:01,800 --> 00:22:12,653
However, quite paradoxically, when the body and mind become full of suffering, when ego, as it were, finds it too painful to live with itself, it wants to rid itself of this painful burden.

287
00:22:12,733 --> 00:22:14,536
What a wonderful trick we play on ourselves.

288
00:22:15,357 --> 00:22:18,541
First ego says, I am my body and mind.

289
00:22:18,942 --> 00:22:19,762
But now it's painful.

290
00:22:19,884 --> 00:22:22,406
Ego says, I'm not really this body and mind.

291
00:22:22,747 --> 00:22:23,468
I can escape it.

292
00:22:24,128 --> 00:22:26,792
But this I is the body and mind.

293
00:22:27,453 --> 00:22:29,557
This ego is that self-identity.

294
00:22:30,337 --> 00:22:39,670
But by a trick of thought, it believes that this self-awareness, which is in fact just another mental concept, exists as a separate substantial entity.

295
00:22:39,650 --> 00:22:46,406
In other words, that the consciousness can somehow leave the body and mind with all its emotions and thinking and go elsewhere.

296
00:22:46,446 --> 00:22:49,474
It says, I think, therefore I am.

297
00:22:50,297 --> 00:22:56,393
The mistake of the philosopher Descartes, if he actually thought that the I was separate from the thinking.

298
00:22:57,030 --> 00:23:03,001
So when this I, this ego, decides to kill off the pain, to commit suicide, it thinks it will escape.

299
00:23:03,762 --> 00:23:16,086
But the Buddha taught that this consciousness is but another of the aggregate, and is part and parcel of mind, not separate from it, equally transient, not permanent, not a substantial entity.

300
00:23:17,010 --> 00:23:23,871
A closer look at the reality of our mental life reveals that consciousness is arising and passing away every minute moment.

301
00:23:24,492 --> 00:23:26,759
Upon death, only the body slumps.

302
00:23:26,779 --> 00:23:28,084
The mind arises again.

303
00:23:28,604 --> 00:23:30,426
The body can be killed, but not the mind.

304
00:23:31,028 --> 00:23:37,798
The mind simply seeks elsewhere, just as it does in everyday life, to satisfy its passions or to rid itself of its suffering.

305
00:23:38,759 --> 00:23:47,253
Suicide turns out to be not an escape, but a further investment in desire, this time in its negative aspects of not wanting aversion.

306
00:23:48,397 --> 00:23:50,421
Annihilation in Buddhism is out of the question.

307
00:23:51,241 --> 00:24:01,857
At base we are propelled through life and from life to life by these two desires, the desire to get, to have, to become, and the desire to be rid of, to annihilate.

308
00:24:04,162 --> 00:24:09,630
Our reactions to such extreme cases will also be dictated by our level of understanding.

309
00:24:10,015 --> 00:24:15,522
If we are but grown-up boys and girls, we will react very much the same way as Lily did when she didn't get her ice cream.

310
00:24:16,002 --> 00:24:16,523
Why me?

311
00:24:17,224 --> 00:24:18,707
Why do I, not the other, have to die?

312
00:24:19,067 --> 00:24:19,728
I'm too young.

313
00:24:21,049 --> 00:24:23,053
Buddhism should prepare us for these realities.

314
00:24:23,854 --> 00:24:32,266
Our meditation, our purification of the mind, the constant attempt to see things as they really are, should undermine these childish attitudes and reactions.

315
00:24:33,547 --> 00:24:37,692
Insofar as we have matured towards our death, so we shall die in peace.

316
00:24:38,432 --> 00:24:45,683
People are always mystified when they hear of someone reacted calmly to the knowledge of their death, as if they wanted people to go screaming.

317
00:24:46,865 --> 00:24:54,596
The 18th century diarist and writer Dr. Johnson, when he went to see the famous philosopher John Locke, was shocked by the man's cheerfulness even though he was dying.

318
00:24:55,739 --> 00:25:00,385
But I ask you, what did the Buddha mean when he said the middle path led to the end of suffering?

319
00:25:01,047 --> 00:25:03,631
Was he not also including the ability to die in peace?

320
00:25:04,372 --> 00:25:06,194
His own death is surely the great model.

321
00:25:06,563 --> 00:25:10,028
Even though he was about to die, he was still giving advice to his followers.

322
00:25:10,848 --> 00:25:14,693
He achieved his parinibbana, total nibbana, in absolute peace and equanimity.

323
00:25:16,075 --> 00:25:21,082
How we react to loss, to being separated from what we love, will be individual and unique.

324
00:25:21,942 --> 00:25:28,030
But we can all reach a point of understanding and a purity of heart where loss is accepted with perfect equanimity.

325
00:25:28,632 --> 00:25:32,757
We can die at peace with the world and in perfect peace within ourselves.

326
00:25:34,188 --> 00:25:36,309
So the question arises, how do we do it?

327
00:25:37,590 --> 00:25:41,776
Now that we've all been meditating full steam for three months or more, you'll know the answer.

328
00:25:42,236 --> 00:25:44,198
The answer is to catch it all in the bud.

329
00:25:44,898 --> 00:25:46,000
To watch it all pass.

330
00:25:46,640 --> 00:25:49,782
To become the objective observer of the mental and emotional life.

331
00:25:50,743 --> 00:25:55,990
When that favourite TV programme comes, watch the desire, the gleeful expectation for it.

332
00:25:56,490 --> 00:25:58,632
Watch it rise, let it pass.

333
00:25:59,333 --> 00:26:03,537
When it's passed, ask yourself, do you really want to watch it?

334
00:26:03,938 --> 00:26:05,320
if you really ought to watch it.

335
00:26:06,483 --> 00:26:10,413
All the time we allow desires to pass and not get caught up in them.

336
00:26:10,432 --> 00:26:12,698
This is purifying the mind of its obsessiveness.

337
00:26:13,740 --> 00:26:20,496
By letting desire go we free the heart and with it the intellect, so that we can truly see what is wholesome for us and what isn't.

338
00:26:21,538 --> 00:26:24,364
Some people think by losing desire they lose the spice of life.

339
00:26:24,683 --> 00:26:25,325
How mistaken.

340
00:26:26,106 --> 00:26:30,634
Desire is the unhealthy additive, like sugar on top of sweet strawberries.

341
00:26:31,355 --> 00:26:33,057
Like all those e-food additives.

342
00:26:33,739 --> 00:26:35,481
We don't know what food really tastes like.

343
00:26:36,324 --> 00:26:38,867
It's the so-called food enhancers we actually taste.

344
00:26:39,588 --> 00:26:41,471
They are what we come to like.

345
00:26:41,451 --> 00:26:44,496
Desire and obsessional emotions are what we come to like.

346
00:26:45,096 --> 00:26:51,744
But just as sugar and ease distort the taste of real food, so desire and obsession distort our sensual experience.

347
00:26:52,546 --> 00:26:55,851
What is more, by letting go of desire, we are preparing for death.

348
00:26:56,751 --> 00:27:01,738
What is it that makes death so painful but our clinging, our obsession, our attachment?

349
00:27:03,740 --> 00:27:05,323
Here's the Buddha in the Dhammapada.

350
00:27:06,585 --> 00:27:08,406
From craving, grief arises.

351
00:27:08,426 --> 00:27:10,869
From craving arises fear.

352
00:27:11,290 --> 00:27:11,391
Fear.

353
00:27:11,809 --> 00:27:14,714
For one who is free of craving, there is no grief.

354
00:27:15,415 --> 00:27:17,298
From where will fear arise?

355
00:27:19,383 --> 00:27:26,515
When the Buddha talks of liberation, liberation from suffering, he does not mean a sudden windfall, a million pounds, so that we can go off and do anything we want.

356
00:27:27,395 --> 00:27:30,662
Mind you, how hard we would work if a million pounds were promised.

357
00:27:31,553 --> 00:27:33,596
No, this liberation is subtler.

358
00:27:33,957 --> 00:27:35,259
It is a freedom from.

359
00:27:35,940 --> 00:27:37,402
It is a release us from prison.

360
00:27:37,942 --> 00:27:43,310
It is an unburdening, as if throwing off a great backpack of bricks we've carried around all our lives.

361
00:27:44,332 --> 00:27:55,890
Freeing ourselves of desire and obsession with all the moods, emotions and feelings they manufacture is to rid ourselves of a huge, constricting, heart-crippling, painful burden.

